Explanation of reasoning:

- I inspected users/routers.go and found UserUpdate handles PUT /api/user.
- I reviewed UserUpdate implementation: it extracts my_user_model from context, uses a validator to bind input, returns 422 Unprocessable Entity with a validator error if binding fails; it attempts to update the user and on database error returns 422 Unprocessable Entity with a generic error; on success it returns 200 OK with a JSON body containing the updated user via UserSerializer.
- I examined UserSerializer in users/serializers.go to determine the shape of the successful response. UserSerializer.Response() returns an object with fields: username (string), email (string), bio (string), image (*string â€” nullable), token (string). The handler wraps that under the top-level "user" key.
- I examined common.NewValidatorError and common.NewError in common/utils.go to determine the error response shape. Both functions return a CommonError which serializes as {"errors": { ... }}. The values in the map are strings (NewError stores err.Error(); NewValidatorError builds string messages), so the errors map is represented as an object with additionalProperties of type string.
- Based on the above, I produced Swagger 2.0 Response Objects (no $ref) for the PUT /api/user endpoint covering:
  - 200: description and schema for {"user": UserResponse}
  - 422: description and schema for {"errors": { <string keys>: <string values> }}

